statement:
Combine the sum of the iterated integrals

\begin{align*}I=\int_0^1\int_{-\sqrt{y}}^{\sqrt{y}}f(x,y)\textrm{d}x\textrm{d}y+\int_1^4\int_{y-2}^{\sqrt{y}}f(x,y)\textrm{d}x\textrm{d}y\end{align*}

into a single iterated integral with the order of integration reversed.

sols:
If we examine the region of integration by drawing a picture...

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.5\textwidth]{MATH200_Dec2012_Q6a.png}
\caption{The domain of integration is enclosed within the curves
$\displaystyle x = y - 2$ (black), ${\color{blue}x = -\sqrt{y}}$ (blue),and ${\color{red}x = \sqrt{y}}$ (red)}
\end{figure}

... we see that if we integrate with respect to y first, that we can
specify the lower bound of integration as $y = x^{2}$ and the upper
bound as $y = x + 2$. Looking at where the lines meet, we can see that
the bounds of integration for x is x = -1 to x = 2. (To find these
intersection points solve the equation $x^{2} = x + 2$.)

From these observations, we can write I as follows\begin{align*}{\color{blue}I = \int_{-1}^{2}\int_{x^{2}}^{x + 2}f(x,y)\,\textrm{d}y\textrm{d}x
}\end{align*}
